                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-28</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>When I was recently recuperating from surgery at home, this series was the first that came to mind as more of a study than a diversion. From the narrative to interviews, it is unforgettable. Mr. Olivier's understated delivery was even at release of this series, imitated (early Dan Akroyd on Saturday Night Live), and such lines as in the "Stalingrad" episode where he quotes Hitler "...we've got it really..." at a very late stage of this battle, are simply definitive. It is clear that a great deal of pain-staking effort went into this series, and is like a favorite movie (though hardly a movie); it can be viewed repeatedly, almost poetic. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">20th Century Iliad</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-11</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>
<br />In an age where documentaries are maybe six one hour episodes at most, seeing "World at War" is quite a revelation. No fewer than 26 one hour episodes, all masterpieces.
<br />
<br />I really loved this series when it aired in the 90s, when I was fourteen. It pretty well started the obsession with history that I still have. But looking on it ten years later, I am even more impressed by this series. 
<br />
<br />Having read thoroughly into World War II, I would have expected this series to begin to appear like other artefacts of childhood - i.e., not as good as I initially thought. But the sheer thoroughness and good judgement shown in these episodes is amazing. There is also some very unusual stuff, such as interviews with Himmler's aide, interviews with Arthur Harris, interviews with Gross Admiral Doenitz (who died an unrepentant Nazi).
<br />
<br />Add to that the superb writing. The spoken narrative is delivered by Laurence Olivier, in a remarkable performance. It is full of choice phrases, such as "The Germans were keeping to the timetable of 1940, not 1914", and, "For one empire, the sun had set; for another, the Sun was still Rising..."
<br />
<br />Overall, this is like the Iliad of World War II. It forms one coherent narrative yet can be watched in individual episodes. One is struck, at the end, by the sheer tragedy of what happened in this, the biggest war of history and THE epic struggle between good and evil in the twentieth century.</span>
                  
